FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - BRAZIL
*****************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Foot & Mouth Disease, cattle - Brazil 980408224343
Foot & Mouth Disease, cattle - Brazil: correction 980415221500
Date: 18, Jan 99
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: Animal Pharm (edited)

[1
FMD returns to Mato Grosso do Sul, Brazil. An outbreak of foot and mouth
disease was detected in the Brazilian state of Mato Grosso do Sul (SW
Brazil) on January 18th, reports the Pan American Foot & Mouth Disease &
Zoonosis Centre (Rio de Janeiro). The outbreak occured in Porto Murtinho,
near the Paraguayan border. The virus has been classified as "O" by the
Recife National Laboratory.
According to official reports, 1,548 cattle were destroyed, eight sheep and
30 pigs. Livestock within a 25 km radius of the outbreak were tested to
ensure that there were no other outbreaks. None were found. Mato gross do
Sul recorded its last FMD out break in February of 1998, which resulted in
the slaughter of 1,800 cattle. The state had been free since August 1994.
In addition ... the northern state of Para announced in January that it
would join the national FMD eradication program. The state, with the
nations fourth largest cattle population (8 million), adopted annual
vaccination in 1998. Two FMD outbreaks were record in Para in 1998.

[2
Date: 29 January 1999
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: OIE reports

FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN BRAZIL
Additional information: Also see OIE reports: 22 January 1999, 27 March
1998, 20 March 1998
Emergency report (see also Disease Information, 12 [2, 7, dated 22 January
1999)
Translation of a fax received on 28 January 1999 from Dr Aluisio Berbert
Sathler, Director, Department of Animal Defence, Ministry of Agriculture
and Supply, Brasilia:
Location: Navirai, State of Mato Grosso do Sul
Number of outbreaks: 2 adjacent holdings
Description of affected population: cattle for fattening.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species bov ovi sui
susceptible 1,548 8 30
cases 101 2 25
deaths ... ... ...
destroyed 1,548 8 30
slaughtered 0 0 0

Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: LAPA, Ministry of Agriculture,
Recife.
B. Diagnostic tests used: ELISA and complement fixation test.
C. Causal agent: FMD virus type O1.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: introduction of cattle from a
source that has yet to be determined.
B. Mode of spread: animal movements.
C. Other epidemiological details: a survey has been carried out within a
25-km radius the outbreaks as well as in all the holdings that received
animals from the outbreaks during the previous 60 days. The survey did not
detect any other outbreaks.
Control measures during reporting period: stamping-out; quarantine and
movement control inside the country; vaccination.
